{GAMBITS BY ESTRIN  Yakov Borisovich Estrin (21 iv 1923 - 2 ii 1987) studied
law in Moscow. He became known as a correspondence chess player. His great
strength was wonderfully shown in gambit games. I have selected twelve
examples.   The next postal game might have been a training for Ludmila
Rudenko, who would become the women's world champion from 1950 until 1953.} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4
15. cxd4 f4 16. f3 Ng3 {They have selected 'La Grande Variante'. It is a late
gambit. Black sacrifices a knight for a mate attack.} 17. hxg3 fxg3 18. Qd3 {
White is going to give a queen for a rook and bishop.} (18. Re1 {
was played in Duras - Maroczy, Oostende 1906.}) 18... Bf5 19. Qxf5 Rxf5 20.
Bxf5 Qh4 21. Bh3 Qxd4+ 22. Kh1 Qxe5 23. Bd2 Qxb2 (23... c5 {
made its debut in Boleslavsky - Ragozin, Moscow 1942.}) 24. Bf4 d4 $5 {
Estrin springs a novelty.} (24... c5 {
won for White in the spectacular game Smyslov - Reshevsky, Radio match 1945.})
25. Rae1 $2 {Rudenko spoils time.} (25. Bxc7 d3 26. Be6+ Kh8 27. Bxg3 {
will be hard to win for Black.}) 25... d3 26. Be5 $6 (26. Bxc7 d2 27. Ra1 Re8
28. Bxg3 Qc2 {brings a strong black attack.}) 26... Qxa2 27. Bxc7 Qc2 28. Rc1
Qb2 29. Be6+ Kh8 30. Bxg3 d2 (30... d2 31. Rc6 $1 Qf6 32. Rd1 Rd8 {
leads to grim prospects for White.}) 0-1

